8 // ----
9 // This pass identifies loops where we can generate the Hexagon hardware ----
10 // loop instruction. The hardware loop can perform loop branches with a ----
11 // zero-cycle overhead. ----
12 // ----
13 // The pattern that defines the induction variable can changed depending on ----
14 // prior optimizations. For example, the IndVarSimplify phase run by 'opt' ----
15 // normalizes induction variables, and the Loop Strength Reduction pass ----
16 // run by 'llc' may also make changes to the induction variable. ----
17 // The pattern detected by this phase is due to running Strength Reduction. ----
18 // ----
19 // Criteria for hardware loops: ----
20 // - Countable loops (w/ ind. var for a trip count) ----
21 // - Assumes loops are normalized by IndVarSimplify ----
22 // - Try inner-most loops first ----
23 // - No function calls in loops. ----
24 // ----
25 //===----------------------------------------------------------------------===// ----
26 ----

129 /// Kinds of comparisons in the compare instructions. ----
130 struct Comparison { ----
131 enum Kind { ----
132 EQ = 0x01, ----
133 NE = 0x02, ----
134 L = 0x04, ----
135 G = 0x08, ----
136 U = 0x40, ----
137 LTs = L, ----
138 LEs = L | EQ, ----
139 GTs = G, ----
140 GEs = G | EQ, ----
141 LTu = L | U, ----
142 LEu = L | EQ | U, ----
143 GTu = G | U, ----
144 GEu = G | EQ | U ----
145 }; ----
146 ----
147 static Kind getSwappedComparison(Kind Cmp) { 0
148 assert ((!((Cmp & L) && (Cmp & G))) && "Malformed comparison operator"); 0
149 if ((Cmp & L) || (Cmp & G)) 0
150 return (Kind)(Cmp ^ (L|G)); 0
151 return Cmp; 0
152 } ----
153 ----
154 static Kind getNegatedComparison(Kind Cmp) { 0
155 if ((Cmp & L) || (Cmp & G)) 0
156 return (Kind)((Cmp ^ (L | G)) ^ EQ); 0
157 if ((Cmp & NE) || (Cmp & EQ)) 0
158 return (Kind)(Cmp ^ (EQ | NE)); 0
159 return (Kind)0; 0
160 } ----
161 ----
162 static bool isSigned(Kind Cmp) { 0
163 return (Cmp & (L | G) && !(Cmp & U)); 0
164 } ----
165 ----
166 static bool isUnsigned(Kind Cmp) { 0
167 return (Cmp & U); 0
168 } ----
169 }; ----

171 /// Find the register that contains the loop controlling ----
172 /// induction variable. ----
173 /// If successful, it will return true and set the \p Reg, \p IVBump ----
174 /// and \p IVOp arguments. Otherwise it will return false. ----
175 /// The returned induction register is the register R that follows the ----
176 /// following induction pattern: ----
177 /// loop: ----
178 /// R = phi ..., [ R.next, LatchBlock ] ----
179 /// R.next = R + #bump ----
180 /// if (R.next < #N) goto loop ----
181 /// IVBump is the immediate value added to R, and IVOp is the instruction ----
182 /// "R.next = R + #bump". ----
183 bool findInductionRegister(MachineLoop *L, Register &Reg, ----
184 int64_t &IVBump, MachineInstr *&IVOp) const; ----
185 ----
186 /// Return the comparison kind for the specified opcode. ----
187 Comparison::Kind getComparisonKind(unsigned CondOpc, ----
188 MachineOperand *InitialValue, ----
189 const MachineOperand *Endvalue, ----
190 int64_t IVBump) const; ----

274 /// Reset the given machine operand to now refer to a new immediate ----
275 /// value. Assumes that the operand was already referencing an immediate ----
276 /// value, either directly, or via a register. ----
277 void setImmediate(MachineOperand &MO, int64_t Val); ----
278 ----
279 /// Fix the data flow of the induction variable. ----
280 /// The desired flow is: phi ---> bump -+-> comparison-in-latch. ----
281 /// | ----
282 /// +-> back to phi ----
283 /// where "bump" is the increment of the induction variable: ----
284 /// iv = iv + #const. ----
285 /// Due to some prior code transformations, the actual flow may look ----
286 /// like this: ----
287 /// phi -+-> bump ---> back to phi ----
288 /// | ----
289 /// +-> comparison-in-latch (against upper_bound-bump), ----
290 /// i.e. the comparison that controls the loop execution may be using ----
291 /// the value of the induction variable from before the increment. ----
292 /// ----
293 /// Return true if the loop's flow is the desired one (i.e. it's ----
294 /// either been fixed, or no fixing was necessary). ----
295 /// Otherwise, return false. This can happen if the induction variable ----
296 /// couldn't be identified, or if the value in the latch's comparison ----
297 /// cannot be adjusted to reflect the post-bump value. ----
298 bool fixupInductionVariable(MachineLoop *L); ----
299 ----
300 /// Given a loop, if it does not have a preheader, create one. ----
301 /// Return the block that is the preheader. ----
302 MachineBasicBlock *createPreheaderForLoop(MachineLoop *L); ----
303 }; ----

310 /// Abstraction for a trip count of a loop. A smaller version ----
311 /// of the MachineOperand class without the concerns of changing the ----
312 /// operand representation. ----
313 class CountValue { ----
314 public: ----
315 enum CountValueType { ----
316 CV_Register, ----
317 CV_Immediate ----
318 }; ----
319 ----
320 private: ----
321 CountValueType Kind; ----
322 union Values { ----
323 Values() : R{Register(), 0} {} 0
324 Values(const Values&) = default; ----
325 struct { ----
326 Register Reg; ----
327 unsigned Sub; ----
328 } R; ----
329 unsigned ImmVal; ----
330 } Contents; ----
331 ----
332 public: ----
333 explicit CountValue(CountValueType t, Register v, unsigned u = 0) { 0
334 Kind = t; 0
335 if (Kind == CV_Register) { 0
336 Contents.R.Reg = v; 0
337 Contents.R.Sub = u; 0
338 } else { ----
339 Contents.ImmVal = v; 0
340 } ----
341 } 0
342 ----
343 bool isReg() const { return Kind == CV_Register; } 0
344 bool isImm() const { return Kind == CV_Immediate; } 0
345 ----
346 Register getReg() const { 0
347 assert(isReg() && "Wrong CountValue accessor"); 0
348 return Contents.R.Reg; 0
349 } ----
350 ----
351 unsigned getSubReg() const { 0
352 assert(isReg() && "Wrong CountValue accessor"); 0
353 return Contents.R.Sub; 0
354 } ----
355 ----
356 unsigned getImm() const { 0
357 assert(isImm() && "Wrong CountValue accessor"); 0
358 return Contents.ImmVal; 0
359 } ----
360 ----
361 void print(raw_ostream &OS, const TargetRegisterInfo *TRI = nullptr) const { ----
362 if (isReg()) { OS << printReg(Contents.R.Reg, TRI, Contents.R.Sub); } ----
363 if (isImm()) { OS << Contents.ImmVal; } ----
364 } ----
365 }; ----

381 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "********* Hexagon Hardware Loops *********\n"); 0
382 if (skipFunction(MF.getFunction())) 0
383 return false; 0
384 ----
385 bool Changed = false; 0
386 ----
387 MLI = &getAnalysis(); 0
388 MRI = &MF.getRegInfo(); 0
389 MDT = &getAnalysis(); 0
390 const HexagonSubtarget &HST = MF.getSubtarget(); 0
391 TII = HST.getInstrInfo(); 0
392 TRI = HST.getRegisterInfo(); 0
393 ----
394 for (auto &L : *MLI) 0
395 if (L->isOutermost()) { 0
396 bool L0Used = false; 0
397 bool L1Used = false; 0
398 Changed |= convertToHardwareLoop(L, L0Used, L1Used); 0
399 } ----
400 ----
401 return Changed; 0

404 bool HexagonHardwareLoops::findInductionRegister(MachineLoop *L, 0
405 Register &Reg, ----
406 int64_t &IVBump, ----
407 MachineInstr *&IVOp ----
408 ) const { ----
409 MachineBasicBlock *Header = L->getHeader(); 0
410 MachineBasicBlock *Preheader = MLI->findLoopPreheader(L, SpecPreheader); 0
411 MachineBasicBlock *Latch = L->getLoopLatch(); 0
412 MachineBasicBlock *ExitingBlock = L->findLoopControlBlock(); 0
413 if (!Header || !Preheader || !Latch || !ExitingBlock) 0
414 return false; 0
415 ----
416 // This pair represents an induction register together with an immediate ----
417 // value that will be added to it in each loop iteration. ----
418 using RegisterBump = std::pair; ----
419 ----
420 // Mapping: R.next -> (R, bump), where R, R.next and bump are derived ----
421 // from an induction operation ----
422 // R.next = R + bump ----
423 // where bump is an immediate value. ----
424 using InductionMap = std::map; ----
425 ----
426 InductionMap IndMap; 0
427 ----
428 using instr_iterator = MachineBasicBlock::instr_iterator; ----
429 ----
430 for (instr_iterator I = Header->instr_begin(), E = Header->instr_end(); 0
431 I != E && I->isPHI(); ++I) { 0
432 MachineInstr *Phi = &*I; 0
433 ----
434 // Have a PHI instruction. Get the operand that corresponds to the ----
435 // latch block, and see if is a result of an addition of form "reg+imm", ----
436 // where the "reg" is defined by the PHI node we are looking at. ----
437 for (unsigned i = 1, n = Phi->getNumOperands(); i < n; i += 2) { 0
438 if (Phi->getOperand(i+1).getMBB() != Latch) 0
439 continue; 0
440 ----
441 Register PhiOpReg = Phi->getOperand(i).getReg(); 0
442 MachineInstr *DI = MRI->getVRegDef(PhiOpReg); 0
443 ----
444 if (DI->getDesc().isAdd()) { 0
445 // If the register operand to the add is the PHI we're looking at, this ----
446 // meets the induction pattern. ----
447 Register IndReg = DI->getOperand(1).getReg(); 0
448 MachineOperand &Opnd2 = DI->getOperand(2); 0
449 int64_t V; ----
450 if (MRI->getVRegDef(IndReg) == Phi && checkForImmediate(Opnd2, V)) { 0
451 Register UpdReg = DI->getOperand(0).getReg(); 0
452 IndMap.insert(std::make_pair(UpdReg, std::make_pair(IndReg, V))); 0
453 } ----
454 } ----
455 } // for (i) ----
456 } // for (instr) ----
457 ----
458 SmallVector Cond; 0
459 MachineBasicBlock *TB = nullptr, *FB = nullptr; 0
460 bool NotAnalyzed = TII->analyzeBranch(*ExitingBlock, TB, FB, Cond, false); 0
461 if (NotAnalyzed) 0
462 return false; 0
463 ----
464 Register PredR; 0
465 unsigned PredPos, PredRegFlags; ----
466 if (!TII->getPredReg(Cond, PredR, PredPos, PredRegFlags)) 0
467 return false; 0
468 ----
469 MachineInstr *PredI = MRI->getVRegDef(PredR); 0
470 if (!PredI->isCompare()) 0
471 return false; 0
472 ----
473 Register CmpReg1, CmpReg2; 0
474 int64_t CmpImm = 0, CmpMask = 0; 0
475 bool CmpAnalyzed = ----
476 TII->analyzeCompare(*PredI, CmpReg1, CmpReg2, CmpMask, CmpImm); 0
477 // Fail if the compare was not analyzed, or it's not comparing a register ----
478 // with an immediate value. Not checking the mask here, since we handle ----
479 // the individual compare opcodes (including A4_cmpb*) later on. ----
480 if (!CmpAnalyzed) 0
481 return false; 0
482 ----
483 // Exactly one of the input registers to the comparison should be among ----
484 // the induction registers. ----
485 InductionMap::iterator IndMapEnd = IndMap.end(); 0
486 InductionMap::iterator F = IndMapEnd; 0
487 if (CmpReg1 != 0) { 0
488 InductionMap::iterator F1 = IndMap.find(CmpReg1); 0
489 if (F1 != IndMapEnd) 0
490 F = F1; 0
491 } ----
492 if (CmpReg2 != 0) { 0
493 InductionMap::iterator F2 = IndMap.find(CmpReg2); 0
494 if (F2 != IndMapEnd) { 0
495 if (F != IndMapEnd) 0
496 return false; 0
497 F = F2; 0
498 } ----
499 } ----
500 if (F == IndMapEnd) 0
501 return false; 0
502 ----
503 Reg = F->second.first; 0
504 IVBump = F->second.second; 0
505 IVOp = MRI->getVRegDef(F->first); 0
506 return true; 0
507 } 0

509 // Return the comparison kind for the specified opcode. ----
510 HexagonHardwareLoops::Comparison::Kind ----
511 HexagonHardwareLoops::getComparisonKind(unsigned CondOpc, 0
512 MachineOperand *InitialValue, ----
513 const MachineOperand *EndValue, ----
514 int64_t IVBump) const { ----
515 Comparison::Kind Cmp = (Comparison::Kind)0; 0
516 switch (CondOpc) { 0
517 case Hexagon::C2_cmpeq: 0
518 case Hexagon::C2_cmpeqi: ----
519 case Hexagon::C2_cmpeqp: ----
520 Cmp = Comparison::EQ; 0
521 break; 0
522 case Hexagon::C4_cmpneq: 0
523 case Hexagon::C4_cmpneqi: ----
524 Cmp = Comparison::NE; 0
525 break; 0
526 case Hexagon::C2_cmplt: 0
527 Cmp = Comparison::LTs; 0
528 break; 0
529 case Hexagon::C2_cmpltu: 0
530 Cmp = Comparison::LTu; 0
531 break; 0
532 case Hexagon::C4_cmplte: 0
533 case Hexagon::C4_cmpltei: ----
534 Cmp = Comparison::LEs; 0
535 break; 0
536 case Hexagon::C4_cmplteu: 0
537 case Hexagon::C4_cmplteui: ----
538 Cmp = Comparison::LEu; 0
539 break; 0
540 case Hexagon::C2_cmpgt: 0
541 case Hexagon::C2_cmpgti: ----
542 case Hexagon::C2_cmpgtp: ----
543 Cmp = Comparison::GTs; 0
544 break; 0
545 case Hexagon::C2_cmpgtu: 0
546 case Hexagon::C2_cmpgtui: ----
547 case Hexagon::C2_cmpgtup: ----
548 Cmp = Comparison::GTu; 0
549 break; 0
550 case Hexagon::C2_cmpgei: 0
551 Cmp = Comparison::GEs; 0
552 break; 0
553 case Hexagon::C2_cmpgeui: 0
554 Cmp = Comparison::GEs; 0
555 break; 0
556 default: 0
557 return (Comparison::Kind)0; 0
558 } ----
559 return Cmp; 0
560 } ----

562 /// Analyze the statements in a loop to determine if the loop has ----
563 /// a computable trip count and, if so, return a value that represents ----
564 /// the trip count expression. ----
565 /// ----
566 /// This function iterates over the phi nodes in the loop to check for ----
567 /// induction variable patterns that are used in the calculation for ----
568 /// the number of time the loop is executed. ----
569 CountValue *HexagonHardwareLoops::getLoopTripCount(MachineLoop *L, 0
570 SmallVectorImpl &OldInsts) { ----
571 MachineBasicBlock *TopMBB = L->getTopBlock(); 0
572 MachineBasicBlock::pred_iterator PI = TopMBB->pred_begin(); 0
573 assert(PI != TopMBB->pred_end() && 0
574 "Loop must have more than one incoming edge!"); ----
575 MachineBasicBlock *Backedge = *PI++; 0
576 if (PI == TopMBB->pred_end()) // dead loop? 0
577 return nullptr; 0
578 MachineBasicBlock *Incoming = *PI++; 0
579 if (PI != TopMBB->pred_end()) // multiple backedges? 0
580 return nullptr; 0
581 ----
582 // Make sure there is one incoming and one backedge and determine which ----
583 // is which. ----
584 if (L->contains(Incoming)) { 0
585 if (L->contains(Backedge)) 0
586 return nullptr; 0
587 std::swap(Incoming, Backedge); 0
588 } else if (!L->contains(Backedge)) 0
589 return nullptr; 0
590 ----
591 // Look for the cmp instruction to determine if we can get a useful trip ----
592 // count. The trip count can be either a register or an immediate. The ----
593 // location of the value depends upon the type (reg or imm). ----
594 MachineBasicBlock *ExitingBlock = L->findLoopControlBlock(); 0
595 if (!ExitingBlock) 0
596 return nullptr; 0
597 ----
598 Register IVReg = 0; 0
599 int64_t IVBump = 0; 0
600 MachineInstr *IVOp; ----
601 bool FoundIV = findInductionRegister(L, IVReg, IVBump, IVOp); 0
602 if (!FoundIV) 0
603 return nullptr; 0
604 ----
605 MachineBasicBlock *Preheader = MLI->findLoopPreheader(L, SpecPreheader); 0
606 ----
607 MachineOperand *InitialValue = nullptr; 0
608 MachineInstr *IV_Phi = MRI->getVRegDef(IVReg); 0
609 MachineBasicBlock *Latch = L->getLoopLatch(); 0
610 for (unsigned i = 1, n = IV_Phi->getNumOperands(); i < n; i += 2) { 0
611 MachineBasicBlock *MBB = IV_Phi->getOperand(i+1).getMBB(); 0
612 if (MBB == Preheader) 0
613 InitialValue = &IV_Phi->getOperand(i); 0
614 else if (MBB == Latch) 0
615 IVReg = IV_Phi->getOperand(i).getReg(); // Want IV reg after bump. 0
616 } ----
617 if (!InitialValue) 0
618 return nullptr; 0
619 ----
620 SmallVector Cond; 0
621 MachineBasicBlock *TB = nullptr, *FB = nullptr; 0
622 bool NotAnalyzed = TII->analyzeBranch(*ExitingBlock, TB, FB, Cond, false); 0
623 if (NotAnalyzed) 0
624 return nullptr; 0
625 ----
626 MachineBasicBlock *Header = L->getHeader(); 0
627 // TB must be non-null. If FB is also non-null, one of them must be ----
628 // the header. Otherwise, branch to TB could be exiting the loop, and ----
629 // the fall through can go to the header. ----
630 assert (TB && "Exit block without a branch?"); 0
631 if (ExitingBlock != Latch && (TB == Latch || FB == Latch)) { 0
632 MachineBasicBlock *LTB = nullptr, *LFB = nullptr; 0
633 SmallVector LCond; 0
634 bool NotAnalyzed = TII->analyzeBranch(*Latch, LTB, LFB, LCond, false); 0
635 if (NotAnalyzed) 0
636 return nullptr; 0
637 if (TB == Latch) 0
638 TB = (LTB == Header) ? LTB : LFB; 0
639 else ----
640 FB = (LTB == Header) ? LTB: LFB; 0
641 } 0
642 assert ((!FB || TB == Header || FB == Header) && "Branches not to header?"); 0
643 if (!TB || (FB && TB != Header && FB != Header)) 0
644 return nullptr; 0
645 ----
646 // Branches of form "if (!P) ..." cause HexagonInstrInfo::analyzeBranch ----
647 // to put imm(0), followed by P in the vector Cond. ----
648 // If TB is not the header, it means that the "not-taken" path must lead ----
649 // to the header. ----
650 bool Negated = TII->predOpcodeHasNot(Cond) ^ (TB != Header); 0
651 Register PredReg; 0
652 unsigned PredPos, PredRegFlags; ----
653 if (!TII->getPredReg(Cond, PredReg, PredPos, PredRegFlags)) 0
654 return nullptr; 0
655 MachineInstr *CondI = MRI->getVRegDef(PredReg); 0
656 unsigned CondOpc = CondI->getOpcode(); 0
657 ----
658 Register CmpReg1, CmpReg2; 0
659 int64_t Mask = 0, ImmValue = 0; 0
660 bool AnalyzedCmp = ----
661 TII->analyzeCompare(*CondI, CmpReg1, CmpReg2, Mask, ImmValue); 0
662 if (!AnalyzedCmp) 0
663 return nullptr; 0
664 ----
665 // The comparison operator type determines how we compute the loop ----
666 // trip count. ----
667 OldInsts.push_back(CondI); 0
668 OldInsts.push_back(IVOp); 0
669 ----
670 // Sadly, the following code gets information based on the position ----
671 // of the operands in the compare instruction. This has to be done ----
672 // this way, because the comparisons check for a specific relationship ----
673 // between the operands (e.g. is-less-than), rather than to find out ----
674 // what relationship the operands are in (as on PPC). ----
675 Comparison::Kind Cmp; ----
676 bool isSwapped = false; 0
677 const MachineOperand &Op1 = CondI->getOperand(1); 0
678 const MachineOperand &Op2 = CondI->getOperand(2); 0
679 const MachineOperand *EndValue = nullptr; 0
680 ----
681 if (Op1.isReg()) { 0
682 if (Op2.isImm() || Op1.getReg() == IVReg) 0
683 EndValue = &Op2; 0
684 else { ----
685 EndValue = &Op1; 0
686 isSwapped = true; 0
687 } ----
688 } ----
689 ----
690 if (!EndValue) 0
691 return nullptr; 0
692 ----
693 Cmp = getComparisonKind(CondOpc, InitialValue, EndValue, IVBump); 0
694 if (!Cmp) 0
695 return nullptr; 0
696 if (Negated) 0
697 Cmp = Comparison::getNegatedComparison(Cmp); 0
698 if (isSwapped) 0
699 Cmp = Comparison::getSwappedComparison(Cmp); 0
700 ----
701 if (InitialValue->isReg()) { 0
702 Register R = InitialValue->getReg(); 0
703 MachineBasicBlock *DefBB = MRI->getVRegDef(R)->getParent(); 0
704 if (!MDT->properlyDominates(DefBB, Header)) { 0
705 int64_t V; ----
706 if (!checkForImmediate(*InitialValue, V)) 0
707 return nullptr; 0
708 } ----
709 OldInsts.push_back(MRI->getVRegDef(R)); 0
710 } ----
711 if (EndValue->isReg()) { 0
712 Register R = EndValue->getReg(); 0
713 MachineBasicBlock *DefBB = MRI->getVRegDef(R)->getParent(); 0
714 if (!MDT->properlyDominates(DefBB, Header)) { 0
715 int64_t V; ----
716 if (!checkForImmediate(*EndValue, V)) 0
717 return nullptr; 0
718 } ----
719 OldInsts.push_back(MRI->getVRegDef(R)); 0
720 } ----
721 ----
722 return computeCount(L, InitialValue, EndValue, IVReg, IVBump, Cmp); 0
723 } 0
724 ----
725 /// Helper function that returns the expression that represents the ----
726 /// number of times a loop iterates. The function takes the operands that ----
727 /// represent the loop start value, loop end value, and induction value. ----
728 /// Based upon these operands, the function attempts to compute the trip count. ----
729 CountValue *HexagonHardwareLoops::computeCount(MachineLoop *Loop, 0
730 const MachineOperand *Start, ----
731 const MachineOperand *End, ----
732 Register IVReg, ----
733 int64_t IVBump, ----
734 Comparison::Kind Cmp) const { ----
735 // Cannot handle comparison EQ, i.e. while (A == B). ----
736 if (Cmp == Comparison::EQ) 0
737 return nullptr; 0
738 ----
739 // Check if either the start or end values are an assignment of an immediate. ----
740 // If so, use the immediate value rather than the register. ----
741 if (Start->isReg()) { 0
742 const MachineInstr *StartValInstr = MRI->getVRegDef(Start->getReg()); 0
743 if (StartValInstr && (StartValInstr->getOpcode() == Hexagon::A2_tfrsi || 0
744 StartValInstr->getOpcode() == Hexagon::A2_tfrpi)) 0
745 Start = &StartValInstr->getOperand(1); 0
746 } ----
747 if (End->isReg()) { 0
748 const MachineInstr *EndValInstr = MRI->getVRegDef(End->getReg()); 0
749 if (EndValInstr && (EndValInstr->getOpcode() == Hexagon::A2_tfrsi || 0
750 EndValInstr->getOpcode() == Hexagon::A2_tfrpi)) 0
751 End = &EndValInstr->getOperand(1); 0
752 } ----
753 ----
754 if (!Start->isReg() && !Start->isImm()) 0
755 return nullptr; 0
756 if (!End->isReg() && !End->isImm()) 0
757 return nullptr; 0
758 ----
759 bool CmpLess = Cmp & Comparison::L; 0
760 bool CmpGreater = Cmp & Comparison::G; 0
761 bool CmpHasEqual = Cmp & Comparison::EQ; 0
762 ----
763 // Avoid certain wrap-arounds. This doesn't detect all wrap-arounds. ----
764 if (CmpLess && IVBump < 0) 0
765 // Loop going while iv is "less" with the iv value going down. Must wrap. ----
766 return nullptr; 0
767 ----
768 if (CmpGreater && IVBump > 0) 0
769 // Loop going while iv is "greater" with the iv value going up. Must wrap. ----
770 return nullptr; 0
771 ----
772 // Phis that may feed into the loop. ----
773 LoopFeederMap LoopFeederPhi; 0
774 ----
775 // Check if the initial value may be zero and can be decremented in the first ----
776 // iteration. If the value is zero, the endloop instruction will not decrement ----
777 // the loop counter, so we shouldn't generate a hardware loop in this case. ----
778 if (loopCountMayWrapOrUnderFlow(Start, End, Loop->getLoopPreheader(), Loop, 0
779 LoopFeederPhi)) ----
780 return nullptr; 0
781 ----
782 if (Start->isImm() && End->isImm()) { 0
783 // Both, start and end are immediates. ----
784 int64_t StartV = Start->getImm(); 0
785 int64_t EndV = End->getImm(); 0
786 int64_t Dist = EndV - StartV; 0
787 if (Dist == 0) 0
788 return nullptr; 0
789 ----
790 bool Exact = (Dist % IVBump) == 0; 0
791 ----
792 if (Cmp == Comparison::NE) { 0
793 if (!Exact) 0
794 return nullptr; 0
795 if ((Dist < 0) ^ (IVBump < 0)) 0
796 return nullptr; 0
797 } ----
798 ----
799 // For comparisons that include the final value (i.e. include equality ----
800 // with the final value), we need to increase the distance by 1. ----
801 if (CmpHasEqual) 0
802 Dist = Dist > 0 ? Dist+1 : Dist-1; 0
803 ----
804 // For the loop to iterate, CmpLess should imply Dist > 0. Similarly, ----
805 // CmpGreater should imply Dist < 0. These conditions could actually ----
806 // fail, for example, in unreachable code (which may still appear to be ----
807 // reachable in the CFG). ----
808 if ((CmpLess && Dist < 0) || (CmpGreater && Dist > 0)) 0
809 return nullptr; 0
810 ----
811 // "Normalized" distance, i.e. with the bump set to +-1. ----
812 int64_t Dist1 = (IVBump > 0) ? (Dist + (IVBump - 1)) / IVBump 0
813 : (-Dist + (-IVBump - 1)) / (-IVBump); 0
814 assert (Dist1 > 0 && "Fishy thing. Both operands have the same sign."); 0
815 ----
816 uint64_t Count = Dist1; 0
817 ----
818 if (Count > 0xFFFFFFFFULL) 0
819 return nullptr; 0
820 ----
821 return new CountValue(CountValue::CV_Immediate, Count); 0
822 } ----
823 ----
824 // A general case: Start and End are some values, but the actual ----
825 // iteration count may not be available. If it is not, insert ----
826 // a computation of it into the preheader. ----
827 ----
828 // If the induction variable bump is not a power of 2, quit. ----
829 // Othwerise we'd need a general integer division. ----
830 if (!isPowerOf2_64(std::abs(IVBump))) 0
831 return nullptr; 0
832 ----
833 MachineBasicBlock *PH = MLI->findLoopPreheader(Loop, SpecPreheader); 0
834 assert (PH && "Should have a preheader by now"); 0
835 MachineBasicBlock::iterator InsertPos = PH->getFirstTerminator(); 0
836 DebugLoc DL; 0
837 if (InsertPos != PH->end()) 0
838 DL = InsertPos->getDebugLoc(); 0
839 ----
840 // If Start is an immediate and End is a register, the trip count ----
841 // will be "reg - imm". Hexagon's "subtract immediate" instruction ----
842 // is actually "reg + -imm". ----
843 ----
844 // If the loop IV is going downwards, i.e. if the bump is negative, ----
845 // then the iteration count (computed as End-Start) will need to be ----
846 // negated. To avoid the negation, just swap Start and End. ----
847 if (IVBump < 0) { 0
848 std::swap(Start, End); 0
849 IVBump = -IVBump; 0
850 } ----
851 // Cmp may now have a wrong direction, e.g. LEs may now be GEs. ----
852 // Signedness, and "including equality" are preserved. ----
853 ----
854 bool RegToImm = Start->isReg() && End->isImm(); // for (reg..imm) 0
855 bool RegToReg = Start->isReg() && End->isReg(); // for (reg..reg) 0
856 ----
857 int64_t StartV = 0, EndV = 0; 0
858 if (Start->isImm()) 0
859 StartV = Start->getImm(); 0
860 if (End->isImm()) 0
861 EndV = End->getImm(); 0
862 ----
863 int64_t AdjV = 0; 0
864 // To compute the iteration count, we would need this computation: ----
865 // Count = (End - Start + (IVBump-1)) / IVBump ----
866 // or, when CmpHasEqual: ----
867 // Count = (End - Start + (IVBump-1)+1) / IVBump ----
868 // The "IVBump-1" part is the adjustment (AdjV). We can avoid ----
869 // generating an instruction specifically to add it if we can adjust ----
870 // the immediate values for Start or End. ----
871 ----
872 if (CmpHasEqual) { 0
873 // Need to add 1 to the total iteration count. ----
874 if (Start->isImm()) 0
875 StartV--; 0
876 else if (End->isImm()) 0
877 EndV++; 0
878 else ----
879 AdjV += 1; 0
880 } ----
881 ----
882 if (Cmp != Comparison::NE) { 0
883 if (Start->isImm()) 0
884 StartV -= (IVBump-1); 0
885 else if (End->isImm()) 0
886 EndV += (IVBump-1); 0
887 else ----
888 AdjV += (IVBump-1); 0
889 } ----
890 ----
891 Register R = 0; 0
892 unsigned SR = 0; 0
893 if (Start->isReg()) { 0
894 R = Start->getReg(); 0
895 SR = Start->getSubReg(); 0
896 } else { ----
897 R = End->getReg(); 0
898 SR = End->getSubReg(); 0
899 } ----
900 const TargetRegisterClass *RC = MRI->getRegClass(R); 0
901 // Hardware loops cannot handle 64-bit registers. If it's a double ----
902 // register, it has to have a subregister. ----
903 if (!SR && RC == &Hexagon::DoubleRegsRegClass) 0
904 return nullptr; 0
905 const TargetRegisterClass *IntRC = &Hexagon::IntRegsRegClass; 0
906 ----
907 // Compute DistR (register with the distance between Start and End). ----
908 Register DistR; 0
909 unsigned DistSR; ----
910 ----
911 // Avoid special case, where the start value is an imm(0). ----
912 if (Start->isImm() && StartV == 0) { 0
913 DistR = End->getReg(); 0
914 DistSR = End->getSubReg(); 0
915 } else { ----
916 const MCInstrDesc &SubD = RegToReg ? TII->get(Hexagon::A2_sub) : 0
917 (RegToImm ? TII->get(Hexagon::A2_subri) : 0
918 TII->get(Hexagon::A2_addi)); 0
919 if (RegToReg || RegToImm) { 0
920 Register SubR = MRI->createVirtualRegister(IntRC); 0
921 MachineInstrBuilder SubIB = ----
922 BuildMI(*PH, InsertPos, DL, SubD, SubR); 0
923 ----
924 if (RegToReg) 0
925 SubIB.addReg(End->getReg(), 0, End->getSubReg()) 0
926 .addReg(Start->getReg(), 0, Start->getSubReg()); 0
927 else ----
928 SubIB.addImm(EndV) 0
929 .addReg(Start->getReg(), 0, Start->getSubReg()); 0
930 DistR = SubR; 0
931 } else { 0
932 // If the loop has been unrolled, we should use the original loop count ----
933 // instead of recalculating the value. This will avoid additional ----
934 // 'Add' instruction. ----
935 const MachineInstr *EndValInstr = MRI->getVRegDef(End->getReg()); 0
936 if (EndValInstr->getOpcode() == Hexagon::A2_addi && 0
937 EndValInstr->getOperand(1).getSubReg() == 0 && 0
938 EndValInstr->getOperand(2).getImm() == StartV) { 0
939 DistR = EndValInstr->getOperand(1).getReg(); 0
940 } else { ----
941 Register SubR = MRI->createVirtualRegister(IntRC); 0
942 MachineInstrBuilder SubIB = ----
943 BuildMI(*PH, InsertPos, DL, SubD, SubR); 0
944 SubIB.addReg(End->getReg(), 0, End->getSubReg()) 0
945 .addImm(-StartV); 0
946 DistR = SubR; 0
947 } ----
948 } ----
949 DistSR = 0; 0
950 } ----
951 ----
952 // From DistR, compute AdjR (register with the adjusted distance). ----
953 Register AdjR; 0
954 unsigned AdjSR; ----
955 ----
956 if (AdjV == 0) { 0
957 AdjR = DistR; 0
958 AdjSR = DistSR; 0
959 } else { ----
960 // Generate CountR = ADD DistR, AdjVal ----
961 Register AddR = MRI->createVirtualRegister(IntRC); 0
962 MCInstrDesc const &AddD = TII->get(Hexagon::A2_addi); 0
963 BuildMI(*PH, InsertPos, DL, AddD, AddR) 0
964 .addReg(DistR, 0, DistSR) 0
965 .addImm(AdjV); 0
966 ----
967 AdjR = AddR; 0
968 AdjSR = 0; 0
969 } ----
970 ----
971 // From AdjR, compute CountR (register with the final count). ----
972 Register CountR; 0
973 unsigned CountSR; ----
974 ----
975 if (IVBump == 1) { 0
976 CountR = AdjR; 0
977 CountSR = AdjSR; 0
978 } else { ----
979 // The IV bump is a power of two. Log_2(IV bump) is the shift amount. ----
980 unsigned Shift = Log2_32(IVBump); 0
981 ----
982 // Generate NormR = LSR DistR, Shift. ----
983 Register LsrR = MRI->createVirtualRegister(IntRC); 0
984 const MCInstrDesc &LsrD = TII->get(Hexagon::S2_lsr_i_r); 0
985 BuildMI(*PH, InsertPos, DL, LsrD, LsrR) 0
986 .addReg(AdjR, 0, AdjSR) 0
987 .addImm(Shift); 0
988 ----
989 CountR = LsrR; 0
990 CountSR = 0; 0
991 } ----
992 ----
993 return new CountValue(CountValue::CV_Register, CountR, CountSR); 0
994 } 0
995 ----
996 /// Return true if the operation is invalid within hardware loop. ----
997 bool HexagonHardwareLoops::isInvalidLoopOperation(const MachineInstr *MI, 0
998 bool IsInnerHWLoop) const { ----
999 // Call is not allowed because the callee may use a hardware loop except for ----
1000 // the case when the call never returns. ----
1001 if (MI->getDesc().isCall()) 0
1002 return !TII->doesNotReturn(*MI); 0
1003 ----
1004 // Check if the instruction defines a hardware loop register. ----
1005 using namespace Hexagon; ----
1006 ----
1007 static const Register Regs01[] = { LC0, SA0, LC1, SA1 }; ----
1008 static const Register Regs1[] = { LC1, SA1 }; ----
1009 auto CheckRegs = IsInnerHWLoop ? ArrayRef(Regs01, std::size(Regs01)) ----
1010 : ArrayRef(Regs1, std::size(Regs1)); 0
1011 for (Register R : CheckRegs) 0
1012 if (MI->modifiesRegister(R, TRI)) 0
1013 return true; 0
1014 ----
1015 return false; 0
1016 } ----
1017 ----
1018 /// Return true if the loop contains an instruction that inhibits ----
1019 /// the use of the hardware loop instruction. ----
1020 bool HexagonHardwareLoops::containsInvalidInstruction(MachineLoop *L, 0
1021 bool IsInnerHWLoop) const { ----
1022 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "\nhw_loop head, " 0
1023 << printMBBReference(**L->block_begin())); ----
1024 for (MachineBasicBlock *MBB : L->getBlocks()) { 0
1025 for (const MachineInstr &MI : *MBB) { 0
1026 if (isInvalidLoopOperation(&MI, IsInnerHWLoop)) { 0
1027 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "\nCannot convert to hw_loop due to:"; 0
1028 MI.dump();); ----
1029 return true; 0
1030 } ----
1031 } ----
1032 } ----
1033 return false; 0
1034 } ----
1035 ----
1036 /// Returns true if the instruction is dead. This was essentially ----
1037 /// copied from DeadMachineInstructionElim::isDead, but with special cases ----
1038 /// for inline asm, physical registers and instructions with side effects ----
1039 /// removed. ----
1040 bool HexagonHardwareLoops::isDead(const MachineInstr *MI, 0
1041 SmallVectorImpl &DeadPhis) const { ----
1042 // Examine each operand. ----
1043 for (const MachineOperand &MO : MI->operands()) { 0
1044 if (!MO.isReg() || !MO.isDef()) 0
1045 continue; 0
1046 ----
1047 Register Reg = MO.getReg(); 0
1048 if (MRI->use_nodbg_empty(Reg)) 0
1049 continue; 0
1050 ----
1051 using use_nodbg_iterator = MachineRegisterInfo::use_nodbg_iterator; ----
1052 ----
1053 // This instruction has users, but if the only user is the phi node for the ----
1054 // parent block, and the only use of that phi node is this instruction, then ----
1055 // this instruction is dead: both it (and the phi node) can be removed. ----
1056 use_nodbg_iterator I = MRI->use_nodbg_begin(Reg); 0
1057 use_nodbg_iterator End = MRI->use_nodbg_end(); 0
1058 if (std::next(I) != End || !I->getParent()->isPHI()) 0
1059 return false; 0
1060 ----
1061 MachineInstr *OnePhi = I->getParent(); 0
1062 for (const MachineOperand &OPO : OnePhi->operands()) { 0
1063 if (!OPO.isReg() || !OPO.isDef()) 0
1064 continue; 0
1065 ----
1066 Register OPReg = OPO.getReg(); 0
1067 use_nodbg_iterator nextJ; 0
1068 for (use_nodbg_iterator J = MRI->use_nodbg_begin(OPReg); 0
1069 J != End; J = nextJ) { 0
1070 nextJ = std::next(J); 0
1071 MachineOperand &Use = *J; 0
1072 MachineInstr *UseMI = Use.getParent(); 0
1073 ----
1074 // If the phi node has a user that is not MI, bail. ----
1075 if (MI != UseMI) 0
1076 return false; 0
1077 } ----
1078 } ----
1079 DeadPhis.push_back(OnePhi); 0
1080 } ----
1081 ----
1082 // If there are no defs with uses, the instruction is dead. ----
1083 return true; 0
1084 } ----
1085 ----
1086 void HexagonHardwareLoops::removeIfDead(MachineInstr *MI) { 0
1087 // This procedure was essentially copied from DeadMachineInstructionElim. ----
1088 ----
1089 SmallVector DeadPhis; 0
1090 if (isDead(MI, DeadPhis)) { 0
1091 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "HW looping will remove: " << *MI); 0
1092 ----
1093 // It is possible that some DBG_VALUE instructions refer to this ----
1094 // instruction. Examine each def operand for such references; ----
1095 // if found, mark the DBG_VALUE as undef (but don't delete it). ----
1096 for (const MachineOperand &MO : MI->operands()) { 0
1097 if (!MO.isReg() || !MO.isDef()) 0
1098 continue; 0
1099 Register Reg = MO.getReg(); 0
1100 // We use make_early_inc_range here because setReg below invalidates the ----
1101 // iterator. ----
1102 for (MachineOperand &MO : 0
1103 llvm::make_early_inc_range(MRI->use_operands(Reg))) { 0
1104 MachineInstr *UseMI = MO.getParent(); 0
1105 if (UseMI == MI) 0
1106 continue; 0
1107 if (MO.isDebug()) 0
1108 MO.setReg(0U); 0
1109 } ----
1110 } ----
1111 ----
1112 MI->eraseFromParent(); 0
1113 for (unsigned i = 0; i < DeadPhis.size(); ++i) 0
1114 DeadPhis[i]->eraseFromParent(); 0
1115 } ----
1116 } 0
1117 ----
1118 /// Check if the loop is a candidate for converting to a hardware ----
1119 /// loop. If so, then perform the transformation. ----
1120 /// ----
1121 /// This function works on innermost loops first. A loop can be converted ----
1122 /// if it is a counting loop; either a register value or an immediate. ----
1123 /// ----
1124 /// The code makes several assumptions about the representation of the loop ----
1125 /// in llvm. ----
1126 bool HexagonHardwareLoops::convertToHardwareLoop(MachineLoop *L, 0
1127 bool &RecL0used, ----
1128 bool &RecL1used) { ----
1129 // This is just to confirm basic correctness. ----
1130 assert(L->getHeader() && "Loop without a header?"); 0
1131 ----
1132 bool Changed = false; 0
1133 bool L0Used = false; 0
1134 bool L1Used = false; 0
1135 ----
1136 // Process nested loops first. ----
1137 for (MachineLoop *I : *L) { 0
1138 Changed |= convertToHardwareLoop(I, RecL0used, RecL1used); 0
1139 L0Used |= RecL0used; 0
1140 L1Used |= RecL1used; 0
1141 } ----
1142 ----
1143 // If a nested loop has been converted, then we can't convert this loop. ----
1144 if (Changed && L0Used && L1Used) 0
1145 return Changed; 0
1146 ----
1147 unsigned LOOP_i; ----
1148 unsigned LOOP_r; ----
1149 unsigned ENDLOOP; ----
1150 ----
1151 // Flag used to track loopN instruction: ----
1152 // 1 - Hardware loop is being generated for the inner most loop. ----
1153 // 0 - Hardware loop is being generated for the outer loop. ----
1154 unsigned IsInnerHWLoop = 1; 0
1155 ----
1156 if (L0Used) { 0
1157 LOOP_i = Hexagon::J2_loop1i; 0
1158 LOOP_r = Hexagon::J2_loop1r; 0
1159 ENDLOOP = Hexagon::ENDLOOP1; 0
1160 IsInnerHWLoop = 0; 0
1161 } else { ----
1162 LOOP_i = Hexagon::J2_loop0i; 0
1163 LOOP_r = Hexagon::J2_loop0r; 0
1164 ENDLOOP = Hexagon::ENDLOOP0; 0
1165 } ----
1166 ----
1167 #ifndef NDEBUG ----
1168 // Stop trying after reaching the limit (if any). ----
1169 int Limit = HWLoopLimit; 0
1170 if (Limit >= 0) { 0
1171 if (Counter >= HWLoopLimit) 0
1172 return false; 0
1173 Counter++; 0
1174 } ----
1175 #endif ----
1176 ----
1177 // Does the loop contain any invalid instructions? ----
1178 if (containsInvalidInstruction(L, IsInnerHWLoop)) 0
1179 return false; 0
1180 ----
1181 MachineBasicBlock *LastMBB = L->findLoopControlBlock(); 0
1182 // Don't generate hw loop if the loop has more than one exit. ----
1183 if (!LastMBB) 0
1184 return false; 0
1185 ----
1186 MachineBasicBlock::iterator LastI = LastMBB->getFirstTerminator(); 0
1187 if (LastI == LastMBB->end()) 0
1188 return false; 0
1189 ----
1190 // Is the induction variable bump feeding the latch condition? ----
1191 if (!fixupInductionVariable(L)) 0
1192 return false; 0
1193 ----
1194 // Ensure the loop has a preheader: the loop instruction will be ----
1195 // placed there. ----
1196 MachineBasicBlock *Preheader = MLI->findLoopPreheader(L, SpecPreheader); 0
1197 if (!Preheader) { 0
1198 Preheader = createPreheaderForLoop(L); 0
1199 if (!Preheader) 0
1200 return false; 0
1201 } ----
1202 ----
1203 MachineBasicBlock::iterator InsertPos = Preheader->getFirstTerminator(); 0
1204 ----
1205 SmallVector OldInsts; 0
1206 // Are we able to determine the trip count for the loop? ----
1207 CountValue *TripCount = getLoopTripCount(L, OldInsts); 0
1208 if (!TripCount) 0
1209 return false; 0
1210 ----
1211 // Is the trip count available in the preheader? ----
1212 if (TripCount->isReg()) { 0
1213 // There will be a use of the register inserted into the preheader, ----
1214 // so make sure that the register is actually defined at that point. ----
1215 MachineInstr *TCDef = MRI->getVRegDef(TripCount->getReg()); 0
1216 MachineBasicBlock *BBDef = TCDef->getParent(); 0
1217 if (!MDT->dominates(BBDef, Preheader)) 0
1218 return false; 0
1219 } ----
1220 ----
1221 // Determine the loop start. ----
1222 MachineBasicBlock *TopBlock = L->getTopBlock(); 0
1223 MachineBasicBlock *ExitingBlock = L->findLoopControlBlock(); 0
1224 MachineBasicBlock *LoopStart = nullptr; 0
1225 if (ExitingBlock != L->getLoopLatch()) { 0
1226 MachineBasicBlock *TB = nullptr, *FB = nullptr; 0
1227 SmallVector Cond; 0
1228 ----
1229 if (TII->analyzeBranch(*ExitingBlock, TB, FB, Cond, false)) 0
1230 return false; 0
1231 ----
1232 if (L->contains(TB)) 0
1233 LoopStart = TB; 0
1234 else if (L->contains(FB)) 0
1235 LoopStart = FB; 0
1236 else ----
1237 return false; 0
1238 } 0
1239 else ----
1240 LoopStart = TopBlock; 0
1241 ----
1242 // Convert the loop to a hardware loop. ----
1243 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Change to hardware loop at "; L->dump()); 0
1244 DebugLoc DL; 0
1245 if (InsertPos != Preheader->end()) 0
1246 DL = InsertPos->getDebugLoc(); 0
1247 ----
1248 if (TripCount->isReg()) { 0
1249 // Create a copy of the loop count register. ----
1250 Register CountReg = MRI->createVirtualRegister(&Hexagon::IntRegsRegClass); 0
1251 BuildMI(*Preheader, InsertPos, DL, TII->get(TargetOpcode::COPY), CountReg) 0
1252 .addReg(TripCount->getReg(), 0, TripCount->getSubReg()); 0
1253 // Add the Loop instruction to the beginning of the loop. ----
1254 BuildMI(*Preheader, InsertPos, DL, TII->get(LOOP_r)).addMBB(LoopStart) 0
1255 .addReg(CountReg); 0
1256 } else { ----
1257 assert(TripCount->isImm() && "Expecting immediate value for trip count"); 0
1258 // Add the Loop immediate instruction to the beginning of the loop, ----
1259 // if the immediate fits in the instructions. Otherwise, we need to ----
1260 // create a new virtual register. ----
1261 int64_t CountImm = TripCount->getImm(); 0
1262 if (!TII->isValidOffset(LOOP_i, CountImm, TRI)) { 0
1263 Register CountReg = MRI->createVirtualRegister(&Hexagon::IntRegsRegClass); 0
1264 BuildMI(*Preheader, InsertPos, DL, TII->get(Hexagon::A2_tfrsi), CountReg) 0
1265 .addImm(CountImm); 0
1266 BuildMI(*Preheader, InsertPos, DL, TII->get(LOOP_r)) 0
1267 .addMBB(LoopStart).addReg(CountReg); 0
1268 } else ----
1269 BuildMI(*Preheader, InsertPos, DL, TII->get(LOOP_i)) 0
1270 .addMBB(LoopStart).addImm(CountImm); 0
1271 } ----
1272 ----
1273 // Make sure the loop start always has a reference in the CFG. ----
1274 LoopStart->setMachineBlockAddressTaken(); 0
1275 ----
1276 // Replace the loop branch with an endloop instruction. ----
1277 DebugLoc LastIDL = LastI->getDebugLoc(); 0
1278 BuildMI(*LastMBB, LastI, LastIDL, TII->get(ENDLOOP)).addMBB(LoopStart); 0
1279 ----
1280 // The loop ends with either: ----
1281 // - a conditional branch followed by an unconditional branch, or ----
1282 // - a conditional branch to the loop start. ----
1283 if (LastI->getOpcode() == Hexagon::J2_jumpt || 0
1284 LastI->getOpcode() == Hexagon::J2_jumpf) { 0
1285 // Delete one and change/add an uncond. branch to out of the loop. ----
1286 MachineBasicBlock *BranchTarget = LastI->getOperand(1).getMBB(); 0
1287 LastI = LastMBB->erase(LastI); 0
1288 if (!L->contains(BranchTarget)) { 0
1289 if (LastI != LastMBB->end()) 0
1290 LastI = LastMBB->erase(LastI); 0
1291 SmallVector Cond; 0
1292 TII->insertBranch(*LastMBB, BranchTarget, nullptr, Cond, LastIDL); 0
1293 } 0
1294 } else { ----
1295 // Conditional branch to loop start; just delete it. ----
1296 LastMBB->erase(LastI); 0
1297 } ----
1298 delete TripCount; 0
1299 ----
1300 // The induction operation and the comparison may now be ----
1301 // unneeded. If these are unneeded, then remove them. ----
1302 for (unsigned i = 0; i < OldInsts.size(); ++i) 0
1303 removeIfDead(OldInsts[i]); 0
1304 ----
1305 ++NumHWLoops; 0
1306 ----
1307 // Set RecL1used and RecL0used only after hardware loop has been ----
1308 // successfully generated. Doing it earlier can cause wrong loop instruction ----
1309 // to be used. ----
1310 if (L0Used) // Loop0 was already used. So, the correct loop must be loop1. 0
1311 RecL1used = true; 0
1312 else ----
1313 RecL0used = true; 0
1314 ----
1315 return true; 0
1316 } 0
1317 ----
1318 bool HexagonHardwareLoops::orderBumpCompare(MachineInstr *BumpI, 0
1319 MachineInstr *CmpI) { ----
1320 assert (BumpI != CmpI && "Bump and compare in the same instruction?"); 0
1321 ----
1322 MachineBasicBlock *BB = BumpI->getParent(); 0
1323 if (CmpI->getParent() != BB) 0
1324 return false; 0
1325 ----
1326 using instr_iterator = MachineBasicBlock::instr_iterator; ----
1327 ----
1328 // Check if things are in order to begin with. ----
1329 for (instr_iterator I(BumpI), E = BB->instr_end(); I != E; ++I) 0
1330 if (&*I == CmpI) 0
1331 return true; 0
1332 ----
1333 // Out of order. ----
1334 Register PredR = CmpI->getOperand(0).getReg(); 0
1335 bool FoundBump = false; 0
1336 instr_iterator CmpIt = CmpI->getIterator(), NextIt = std::next(CmpIt); 0
1337 for (instr_iterator I = NextIt, E = BB->instr_end(); I != E; ++I) { 0
1338 MachineInstr *In = &*I; 0
1339 for (unsigned i = 0, n = In->getNumOperands(); i < n; ++i) { 0
1340 MachineOperand &MO = In->getOperand(i); 0
1341 if (MO.isReg() && MO.isUse()) { 0
1342 if (MO.getReg() == PredR) // Found an intervening use of PredR. 0
1343 return false; 0
1344 } ----
1345 } ----
1346 ----
1347 if (In == BumpI) { 0
1348 BB->splice(++BumpI->getIterator(), BB, CmpI->getIterator()); 0
1349 FoundBump = true; 0
1350 break; 0
1351 } ----
1352 } ----
1353 assert (FoundBump && "Cannot determine instruction order"); 0
1354 return FoundBump; 0
1355 } ----
1356 ----
1357 /// This function is required to break recursion. Visiting phis in a loop may ----
1358 /// result in recursion during compilation. We break the recursion by making ----
1359 /// sure that we visit a MachineOperand and its definition in a ----
1360 /// MachineInstruction only once. If we attempt to visit more than once, then ----
1361 /// there is recursion, and will return false. ----
1362 bool HexagonHardwareLoops::isLoopFeeder(MachineLoop *L, MachineBasicBlock *A, 0
1363 MachineInstr *MI, ----
1364 const MachineOperand *MO, ----
1365 LoopFeederMap &LoopFeederPhi) const { ----
1366 if (LoopFeederPhi.find(MO->getReg()) == LoopFeederPhi.end()) { 0
1367 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "\nhw_loop head, " 0
1368 << printMBBReference(**L->block_begin())); ----
1369 // Ignore all BBs that form Loop. ----
1370 if (llvm::is_contained(L->getBlocks(), A)) 0
1371 return false; 0
1372 MachineInstr *Def = MRI->getVRegDef(MO->getReg()); 0
1373 LoopFeederPhi.insert(std::make_pair(MO->getReg(), Def)); 0
1374 return true; 0
1375 } else ----
1376 // Already visited node. ----
1377 return false; 0
1378 } ----
1379 ----
1380 /// Return true if a Phi may generate a value that can underflow. ----
1381 /// This function calls loopCountMayWrapOrUnderFlow for each Phi operand. ----
1382 bool HexagonHardwareLoops::phiMayWrapOrUnderflow( 0
1383 MachineInstr *Phi, const MachineOperand *EndVal, MachineBasicBlock *MBB, ----
1384 MachineLoop *L, LoopFeederMap &LoopFeederPhi) const { ----
1385 assert(Phi->isPHI() && "Expecting a Phi."); 0
1386 // Walk through each Phi, and its used operands. Make sure that ----
1387 // if there is recursion in Phi, we won't generate hardware loops. ----
1388 for (int i = 1, n = Phi->getNumOperands(); i < n; i += 2) 0
1389 if (isLoopFeeder(L, MBB, Phi, &(Phi->getOperand(i)), LoopFeederPhi)) 0
1390 if (loopCountMayWrapOrUnderFlow(&(Phi->getOperand(i)), EndVal, 0
1391 Phi->getParent(), L, LoopFeederPhi)) ----
1392 return true; 0
1393 return false; 0
1394 } ----
1395 ----
1396 /// Return true if the induction variable can underflow in the first iteration. ----
1397 /// An example, is an initial unsigned value that is 0 and is decrement in the ----
1398 /// first itertion of a do-while loop. In this case, we cannot generate a ----
1399 /// hardware loop because the endloop instruction does not decrement the loop ----
1400 /// counter if it is <= 1. We only need to perform this analysis if the ----
1401 /// initial value is a register. ----
1402 /// ----
1403 /// This function assumes the initial value may underfow unless proven ----
1404 /// otherwise. If the type is signed, then we don't care because signed ----
1405 /// underflow is undefined. We attempt to prove the initial value is not ----
1406 /// zero by perfoming a crude analysis of the loop counter. This function ----
1407 /// checks if the initial value is used in any comparison prior to the loop ----
1408 /// and, if so, assumes the comparison is a range check. This is inexact, ----
1409 /// but will catch the simple cases. ----
1410 bool HexagonHardwareLoops::loopCountMayWrapOrUnderFlow( 0
1411 const MachineOperand *InitVal, const MachineOperand *EndVal, ----
1412 MachineBasicBlock *MBB, MachineLoop *L, ----
1413 LoopFeederMap &LoopFeederPhi) const { ----
1414 // Only check register values since they are unknown. ----
1415 if (!InitVal->isReg()) 0
1416 return false; 0
1417 ----
1418 if (!EndVal->isImm()) 0
1419 return false; 0
1420 ----
1421 // A register value that is assigned an immediate is a known value, and it ----
1422 // won't underflow in the first iteration. ----
1423 int64_t Imm; ----
1424 if (checkForImmediate(*InitVal, Imm)) 0
1425 return (EndVal->getImm() == Imm); 0
1426 ----
1427 Register Reg = InitVal->getReg(); 0
1428 ----
1429 // We don't know the value of a physical register. ----
1430 if (!Reg.isVirtual()) 0
1431 return true; 0
1432 ----
1433 MachineInstr *Def = MRI->getVRegDef(Reg); 0
1434 if (!Def) 0
1435 return true; 0
1436 ----
1437 // If the initial value is a Phi or copy and the operands may not underflow, ----
1438 // then the definition cannot be underflow either. ----
1439 if (Def->isPHI() && !phiMayWrapOrUnderflow(Def, EndVal, Def->getParent(), 0
1440 L, LoopFeederPhi)) ----
1441 return false; 0
1442 if (Def->isCopy() && !loopCountMayWrapOrUnderFlow(&(Def->getOperand(1)), 0
1443 EndVal, Def->getParent(), ----
1444 L, LoopFeederPhi)) ----
1445 return false; 0
1446 ----
1447 // Iterate over the uses of the initial value. If the initial value is used ----
1448 // in a compare, then we assume this is a range check that ensures the loop ----
1449 // doesn't underflow. This is not an exact test and should be improved. ----
1450 for (MachineRegisterInfo::use_instr_nodbg_iterator I = MRI->use_instr_nodbg_begin(Reg), 0
1451 E = MRI->use_instr_nodbg_end(); I != E; ++I) { 0
1452 MachineInstr *MI = &*I; 0
1453 Register CmpReg1, CmpReg2; 0
1454 int64_t CmpMask = 0, CmpValue = 0; 0
1455 ----
1456 if (!TII->analyzeCompare(*MI, CmpReg1, CmpReg2, CmpMask, CmpValue)) 0
1457 continue; 0
1458 ----
1459 MachineBasicBlock *TBB = nullptr, *FBB = nullptr; 0
1460 SmallVector Cond; 0
1461 if (TII->analyzeBranch(*MI->getParent(), TBB, FBB, Cond, false)) 0
1462 continue; 0
1463 ----
1464 Comparison::Kind Cmp = ----
1465 getComparisonKind(MI->getOpcode(), nullptr, nullptr, 0); 0
1466 if (Cmp == 0) 0
1467 continue; 0
1468 if (TII->predOpcodeHasNot(Cond) ^ (TBB != MBB)) 0
1469 Cmp = Comparison::getNegatedComparison(Cmp); 0
1470 if (CmpReg2 != 0 && CmpReg2 == Reg) 0
1471 Cmp = Comparison::getSwappedComparison(Cmp); 0
1472 ----
1473 // Signed underflow is undefined. ----
1474 if (Comparison::isSigned(Cmp)) 0
1475 return false; 0
1476 ----
1477 // Check if there is a comparison of the initial value. If the initial value ----
1478 // is greater than or not equal to another value, then assume this is a ----
1479 // range check. ----
1480 if ((Cmp & Comparison::G) || Cmp == Comparison::NE) 0
1481 return false; 0
1482 } 0
1483 ----
1484 // OK - this is a hack that needs to be improved. We really need to analyze ----
1485 // the instructions performed on the initial value. This works on the simplest ----
1486 // cases only. ----
1487 if (!Def->isCopy() && !Def->isPHI()) 0
1488 return false; 0
1489 ----
1490 return true; 0
1491 } ----
1492 ----
1493 bool HexagonHardwareLoops::checkForImmediate(const MachineOperand &MO, 0
1494 int64_t &Val) const { ----
1495 if (MO.isImm()) { 0
1496 Val = MO.getImm(); 0
1497 return true; 0
1498 } ----
1499 if (!MO.isReg()) 0
1500 return false; 0
1501 ----
1502 // MO is a register. Check whether it is defined as an immediate value, ----
1503 // and if so, get the value of it in TV. That value will then need to be ----
1504 // processed to handle potential subregisters in MO. ----
1505 int64_t TV; ----
1506 ----
1507 Register R = MO.getReg(); 0
1508 if (!R.isVirtual()) 0
1509 return false; 0
1510 MachineInstr *DI = MRI->getVRegDef(R); 0
1511 unsigned DOpc = DI->getOpcode(); 0
1512 switch (DOpc) { 0
1513 case TargetOpcode::COPY: 0
1514 case Hexagon::A2_tfrsi: ----
1515 case Hexagon::A2_tfrpi: ----
1516 case Hexagon::CONST32: ----
1517 case Hexagon::CONST64: ----
1518 // Call recursively to avoid an extra check whether operand(1) is ----
1519 // indeed an immediate (it could be a global address, for example), ----
1520 // plus we can handle COPY at the same time. ----
1521 if (!checkForImmediate(DI->getOperand(1), TV)) 0
1522 return false; 0
1523 break; 0
1524 case Hexagon::A2_combineii: 0
1525 case Hexagon::A4_combineir: ----
1526 case Hexagon::A4_combineii: ----
1527 case Hexagon::A4_combineri: ----
1528 case Hexagon::A2_combinew: { ----
1529 const MachineOperand &S1 = DI->getOperand(1); 0
1530 const MachineOperand &S2 = DI->getOperand(2); 0
1531 int64_t V1, V2; ----
1532 if (!checkForImmediate(S1, V1) || !checkForImmediate(S2, V2)) 0
1533 return false; 0
1534 TV = V2 | (static_cast(V1) << 32); 0
1535 break; 0
1536 } ----
1537 case TargetOpcode::REG_SEQUENCE: { 0
1538 const MachineOperand &S1 = DI->getOperand(1); 0
1539 const MachineOperand &S3 = DI->getOperand(3); 0
1540 int64_t V1, V3; ----
1541 if (!checkForImmediate(S1, V1) || !checkForImmediate(S3, V3)) 0
1542 return false; 0
1543 unsigned Sub2 = DI->getOperand(2).getImm(); 0
1544 unsigned Sub4 = DI->getOperand(4).getImm(); 0
1545 if (Sub2 == Hexagon::isub_lo && Sub4 == Hexagon::isub_hi) 0
1546 TV = V1 | (V3 << 32); 0
1547 else if (Sub2 == Hexagon::isub_hi && Sub4 == Hexagon::isub_lo) 0
1548 TV = V3 | (V1 << 32); 0
1549 else ----
1550 llvm_unreachable("Unexpected form of REG_SEQUENCE"); 0
1551 break; 0
1552 } ----
1553 ----
1554 default: 0
1555 return false; 0
1556 } ----
1557 ----
1558 // By now, we should have successfully obtained the immediate value defining ----
1559 // the register referenced in MO. Handle a potential use of a subregister. ----
1560 switch (MO.getSubReg()) { 0
1561 case Hexagon::isub_lo: 0
1562 Val = TV & 0xFFFFFFFFULL; 0
1563 break; 0
1564 case Hexagon::isub_hi: 0
1565 Val = (TV >> 32) & 0xFFFFFFFFULL; 0
1566 break; 0
1567 default: 0
1568 Val = TV; 0
1569 break; 0
1570 } ----
1571 return true; 0
1572 } ----
1573 ----
1574 void HexagonHardwareLoops::setImmediate(MachineOperand &MO, int64_t Val) { 0
1575 if (MO.isImm()) { 0
1576 MO.setImm(Val); 0
1577 return; 0
1578 } ----
1579 ----
1580 assert(MO.isReg()); 0
1581 Register R = MO.getReg(); 0
1582 MachineInstr *DI = MRI->getVRegDef(R); 0
1583 ----
1584 const TargetRegisterClass *RC = MRI->getRegClass(R); 0
1585 Register NewR = MRI->createVirtualRegister(RC); 0
1586 MachineBasicBlock &B = *DI->getParent(); 0
1587 DebugLoc DL = DI->getDebugLoc(); 0
1588 BuildMI(B, DI, DL, TII->get(DI->getOpcode()), NewR).addImm(Val); 0
1589 MO.setReg(NewR); 0
1590 } 0
1591 ----
1592 bool HexagonHardwareLoops::fixupInductionVariable(MachineLoop *L) { 0
1593 MachineBasicBlock *Header = L->getHeader(); 0
1594 MachineBasicBlock *Latch = L->getLoopLatch(); 0
1595 MachineBasicBlock *ExitingBlock = L->findLoopControlBlock(); 0
1596 ----
1597 if (!(Header && Latch && ExitingBlock)) 0
1598 return false; 0
1599 ----
1600 // These data structures follow the same concept as the corresponding ----
1601 // ones in findInductionRegister (where some comments are). ----
1602 using RegisterBump = std::pair; ----
1603 using RegisterInduction = std::pair; ----
1604 using RegisterInductionSet = std::set; ----
1605 ----
1606 // Register candidates for induction variables, with their associated bumps. ----
1607 RegisterInductionSet IndRegs; 0
1608 ----
1609 // Look for induction patterns: ----
1610 // %1 = PHI ..., [ latch, %2 ] ----
1611 // %2 = ADD %1, imm ----
1612 using instr_iterator = MachineBasicBlock::instr_iterator; ----
1613 ----
1614 for (instr_iterator I = Header->instr_begin(), E = Header->instr_end(); 0
1615 I != E && I->isPHI(); ++I) { 0
1616 MachineInstr *Phi = &*I; 0
1617 ----
1618 // Have a PHI instruction. ----
1619 for (unsigned i = 1, n = Phi->getNumOperands(); i < n; i += 2) { 0
1620 if (Phi->getOperand(i+1).getMBB() != Latch) 0
1621 continue; 0
1622 ----
1623 Register PhiReg = Phi->getOperand(i).getReg(); 0
1624 MachineInstr *DI = MRI->getVRegDef(PhiReg); 0
1625 ----
1626 if (DI->getDesc().isAdd()) { 0
1627 // If the register operand to the add/sub is the PHI we are looking ----
1628 // at, this meets the induction pattern. ----
1629 Register IndReg = DI->getOperand(1).getReg(); 0
1630 MachineOperand &Opnd2 = DI->getOperand(2); 0
1631 int64_t V; ----
1632 if (MRI->getVRegDef(IndReg) == Phi && checkForImmediate(Opnd2, V)) { 0
1633 Register UpdReg = DI->getOperand(0).getReg(); 0
1634 IndRegs.insert(std::make_pair(UpdReg, std::make_pair(IndReg, V))); 0
1635 } ----
1636 } ----
1637 } // for (i) ----
1638 } // for (instr) ----
1639 ----
1640 if (IndRegs.empty()) 0
1641 return false; 0
1642 ----
1643 MachineBasicBlock *TB = nullptr, *FB = nullptr; 0
1644 SmallVector Cond; 0
1645 // analyzeBranch returns true if it fails to analyze branch. ----
1646 bool NotAnalyzed = TII->analyzeBranch(*ExitingBlock, TB, FB, Cond, false); 0
1647 if (NotAnalyzed || Cond.empty()) 0
1648 return false; 0
1649 ----
1650 if (ExitingBlock != Latch && (TB == Latch || FB == Latch)) { 0
1651 MachineBasicBlock *LTB = nullptr, *LFB = nullptr; 0
1652 SmallVector LCond; 0
1653 bool NotAnalyzed = TII->analyzeBranch(*Latch, LTB, LFB, LCond, false); 0
1654 if (NotAnalyzed) 0
1655 return false; 0
1656 ----
1657 // Since latch is not the exiting block, the latch branch should be an ----
1658 // unconditional branch to the loop header. ----
1659 if (TB == Latch) 0
1660 TB = (LTB == Header) ? LTB : LFB; 0
1661 else ----
1662 FB = (LTB == Header) ? LTB : LFB; 0
1663 } 0
1664 if (TB != Header) { 0
1665 if (FB != Header) { 0
1666 // The latch/exit block does not go back to the header. ----
1667 return false; 0
1668 } ----
1669 // FB is the header (i.e., uncond. jump to branch header) ----
1670 // In this case, the LoopBody -> TB should not be a back edge otherwise ----
1671 // it could result in an infinite loop after conversion to hw_loop. ----
1672 // This case can happen when the Latch has two jumps like this: ----
1673 // Jmp_c OuterLoopHeader <-- TB ----
1674 // Jmp InnerLoopHeader <-- FB ----
1675 if (MDT->dominates(TB, FB)) 0
1676 return false; 0
1677 } ----
1678 ----
1679 // Expecting a predicate register as a condition. It won't be a hardware ----
1680 // predicate register at this point yet, just a vreg. ----
1681 // HexagonInstrInfo::analyzeBranch for negated branches inserts imm(0) ----
1682 // into Cond, followed by the predicate register. For non-negated branches ----
1683 // it's just the register. ----
1684 unsigned CSz = Cond.size(); 0
1685 if (CSz != 1 && CSz != 2) 0
1686 return false; 0
1687 ----
1688 if (!Cond[CSz-1].isReg()) 0
1689 return false; 0
1690 ----
1691 Register P = Cond[CSz - 1].getReg(); 0
1692 MachineInstr *PredDef = MRI->getVRegDef(P); 0
1693 ----
1694 if (!PredDef->isCompare()) 0
1695 return false; 0
1696 ----
1697 SmallSet CmpRegs; 0
1698 MachineOperand *CmpImmOp = nullptr; 0
1699 ----
1700 // Go over all operands to the compare and look for immediate and register ----
1701 // operands. Assume that if the compare has a single register use and a ----
1702 // single immediate operand, then the register is being compared with the ----
1703 // immediate value. ----
1704 for (MachineOperand &MO : PredDef->operands()) { 0
1705 if (MO.isReg()) { 0
1706 // Skip all implicit references. In one case there was: ----
1707 // %140 = FCMPUGT32_rr %138, %139, implicit %usr ----
1708 if (MO.isImplicit()) 0
1709 continue; 0
1710 if (MO.isUse()) { 0
1711 if (!isImmediate(MO)) { 0
1712 CmpRegs.insert(MO.getReg()); 0
1713 continue; 0
1714 } ----
1715 // Consider the register to be the "immediate" operand. ----
1716 if (CmpImmOp) 0
1717 return false; 0
1718 CmpImmOp = &MO; 0
1719 } ----
1720 } else if (MO.isImm()) { 0
1721 if (CmpImmOp) // A second immediate argument? Confusing. Bail out. 0
1722 return false; 0
1723 CmpImmOp = &MO; 0
1724 } ----
1725 } ----
1726 ----
1727 if (CmpRegs.empty()) 0
1728 return false; 0
1729 ----
1730 // Check if the compared register follows the order we want. Fix if needed. ----
1731 for (RegisterInductionSet::iterator I = IndRegs.begin(), E = IndRegs.end(); 0
1732 I != E; ++I) { 0
1733 // This is a success. If the register used in the comparison is one that ----
1734 // we have identified as a bumped (updated) induction register, there is ----
1735 // nothing to do. ----
1736 if (CmpRegs.count(I->first)) 0
1737 return true; 0
1738 ----
1739 // Otherwise, if the register being compared comes out of a PHI node, ----
1740 // and has been recognized as following the induction pattern, and is ----
1741 // compared against an immediate, we can fix it. ----
1742 const RegisterBump &RB = I->second; 0
1743 if (CmpRegs.count(RB.first)) { 0
1744 if (!CmpImmOp) { 0
1745 // If both operands to the compare instruction are registers, see if ----
1746 // it can be changed to use induction register as one of the operands. ----
1747 MachineInstr *IndI = nullptr; 0
1748 MachineInstr *nonIndI = nullptr; 0
1749 MachineOperand *IndMO = nullptr; 0
1750 MachineOperand *nonIndMO = nullptr; 0
1751 ----
1752 for (unsigned i = 1, n = PredDef->getNumOperands(); i < n; ++i) { 0
1753 MachineOperand &MO = PredDef->getOperand(i); 0
1754 if (MO.isReg() && MO.getReg() == RB.first) { 0
1755 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "\n DefMI(" << i 0
1756 << ") = " << *(MRI->getVRegDef(I->first))); ----
1757 if (IndI) 0
1758 return false; 0
1759 ----
1760 IndI = MRI->getVRegDef(I->first); 0
1761 IndMO = &MO; 0
1762 } else if (MO.isReg()) { 0
1763 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "\n DefMI(" << i 0
1764 << ") = " << *(MRI->getVRegDef(MO.getReg()))); ----
1765 if (nonIndI) 0
1766 return false; 0
1767 ----
1768 nonIndI = MRI->getVRegDef(MO.getReg()); 0
1769 nonIndMO = &MO; 0
1770 } ----
1771 } ----
1772 if (IndI && nonIndI && 0
1773 nonIndI->getOpcode() == Hexagon::A2_addi && 0
1774 nonIndI->getOperand(2).isImm() && 0
1775 nonIndI->getOperand(2).getImm() == - RB.second) { 0
1776 bool Order = orderBumpCompare(IndI, PredDef); 0
1777 if (Order) { 0
1778 IndMO->setReg(I->first); 0
1779 nonIndMO->setReg(nonIndI->getOperand(1).getReg()); 0
1780 return true; 0
1781 } ----
1782 } ----
1783 return false; 0
1784 } ----
1785 ----
1786 // It is not valid to do this transformation on an unsigned comparison ----
1787 // because it may underflow. ----
1788 Comparison::Kind Cmp = ----
1789 getComparisonKind(PredDef->getOpcode(), nullptr, nullptr, 0); 0
1790 if (!Cmp || Comparison::isUnsigned(Cmp)) 0
1791 return false; 0
1792 ----
